"2 weeks ago  3      0.3    Mickey Mouse   <cheddar@gmouse.org>\n"
"a month ago  927    99.7   Minnie Mouse   <swiss@mouse.org>\n"
"\n"
"2 weeks ago  930    100.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:585
msgid ""
"By default, you will get a table view (shown above) sorted by date of "
"contribution, with the most recent contribution at the top.  If you want to "
"sort instead by percentage of code contribution, then add ``-p``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:589
msgid "$ spack blame -p python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:594
msgid "And to see the git blame view, add ``-g`` instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:597
msgid "$ spack blame -g python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:602
msgid "Finally, to get a json export of the data, add ``--json``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:604
msgid "$ spack blame --json python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:611
msgid "``spack url``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:613
msgid ""
"A package containing a single URL can be used to download several different "
"versions of the package. If you've ever wondered how this works, all of the "
"magic is in :mod:`spack.url`. This module contains methods for extracting "
"the name and version of a package from its URL. The name is used by ``spack "
"create`` to guess the name of the package. By determining the version from "
"the URL, Spack can replace it with other versions to determine where to "
"download them from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:621
msgid ""
"The regular expressions in ``parse_name_offset`` and "
"``parse_version_offset`` are used to extract the name and version, but they "
"aren't perfect. In order to debug Spack's URL parsing support, the ``spack "
"url`` command can be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:627
msgid "``spack url parse``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:629
msgid "If you need to debug a single URL, you can use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:633
msgid ""
"You'll notice that the name and version of this URL are correctly detected, "
"and you can even see which regular expressions it was matched to. However, "
"you'll notice that when it substitutes the version number in, it doesn't "
"replace the ``2.2`` with ``9.9`` where we would expect ``9.9.9b`` to live. "
"This particular package may require a ``list_url`` or ``url_for_version`` "
"function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:640
msgid ""
"This command also accepts a ``--spider`` flag. If provided, Spack searches "
"for other versions of the package and prints the matching URLs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:645
msgid "``spack url list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:647
msgid ""
"This command lists every URL in every package in Spack. If given the ``--"
"color`` and ``--extrapolation`` flags, it also colors the part of the string "
"that it detected to be the name and version. The ``--incorrect-name`` and "
"``--incorrect-version`` flags can be used to print URLs that were not being "
"parsed correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:655
msgid "``spack url summary``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:657
msgid ""
"This command attempts to parse every URL for every package in Spack and "
"prints a summary of how many of them are being correctly parsed. It also "
"prints a histogram showing which regular expressions are being matched and "
"how frequently:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:664
msgid ""
"This command is essential for anyone adding or changing the regular "
"expressions that parse names and versions. By running this command before "
"and after the change, you can make sure that your regular expression fixes "
"more packages than it breaks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:671
msgid "Profiling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:673
msgid ""
"Spack has some limited built-in support for profiling, and can report "
"statistics using standard Python timing tools.  To use this feature, supply "
"``--profile`` to Spack on the command line, before any subcommands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:681
msgid "``spack --profile``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:683
msgid "``spack --profile`` output looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:688
msgid ""
"The bottom of the output shows the top most time consuming functions, "
"slowest on top.  The profiling support is from Python's built-in tool, "
"`cProfile <https://docs.python.org/2/library/profile.html#module-cProfile>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:697
msgid "Releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:699
msgid ""
"This section documents Spack's release process. It is intended for project "
"maintainers, as the tasks described here require maintainer privileges on "
"the Spack repository. For others, we hope this section at least provides "
"some insight into how the Spack project works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:708
msgid "Release branches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:710
msgid ""
"There are currently two types of Spack releases: :ref:`major releases <major-"
"releases>` (``0.21.0``, ``0.22.0``, etc.) and :ref:`patch releases <patch-"
"releases>` (``0.22.1``, ``0.22.2``, ``0.22.3``, etc.). Here is a diagram of "
"how Spack release branches work::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:715
msgid ""
"o    branch: develop  (latest version, v0.23.0.dev0)\n"
"|\n"
"o\n"
"| o  branch: releases/v0.22, tag: v0.22.1\n"
"o |\n"
"| o  tag: v0.22.0\n"
"o |\n"
"| o\n"
"|/\n"
"o\n"
"|\n"
"o\n"
"| o  branch: releases/v0.21, tag: v0.21.2\n"
"o |\n"
"| o  tag: v0.21.1\n"
"o |\n"
"| o  tag: v0.21.0\n"
"o |\n"
"| o\n"
"|/\n"
"o"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:737
msgid ""
"The ``develop`` branch has the latest contributions, and nearly all pull "
"requests target ``develop``. The ``develop`` branch will report that its "
"version is that of the next **major** release with a ``.dev0`` suffix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:741
msgid ""
"Each Spack release series also has a corresponding branch, e.g. ``releases/"
"v0.22`` has ``v0.22.x`` versions of Spack, and ``releases/v0.21`` has "
"``v0.21.x`` versions. A major release is the first tagged version on a "
"release branch. Minor releases are back-ported from develop onto release "
"branches. This is typically done by cherry-picking bugfix commits off of "
"``develop``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:748
msgid ""
"To avoid version churn for users of a release series, minor releases "
"**should not** make changes that would change the concretization of "
"packages. They should generally only contain fixes to the Spack core. "
"However, sometimes priorities are such that new functionality needs to be "
"added to a minor release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:754
msgid ""
"Both major and minor releases are tagged. As a convenience, we also tag the "
"latest release as ``releases/latest``, so that users can easily check it out "
"to get the latest stable version. See :ref:`updating-latest-release` for "
"more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:761
msgid ""
"Older spack releases were merged **back** into develop so that we could do "
"fancy things with tags, but since tarballs and many git checkouts do not "
"have tags, this proved overly complex and confusing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:765
msgid ""
"We have since converted to using `PEP 440 <https://peps.python.org/pep-0440/"
">`_ compliant versions.  `See here <https://github.com/spack/spack/"
"pull/25267>`_ for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:771
msgid "Scheduling work for releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:773
msgid ""
"We schedule work for **major releases** through `milestones <https://github."
"com/spack/spack/milestones>`_ and `GitHub Projects <https://github.com/spack/"
"spack/projects>`_, while **patch releases** use `labels <https://github.com/"
"spack/spack/labels>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:778
msgid ""
"There is only one milestone open at a time. Its name corresponds to the next "
"major version, for example ``v0.23``. Important issues and pull requests "
"should be assigned to this milestone by core developers, so that they are "
"not forgotten at the time of release. The milestone is closed when the "
"release is made, and a new milestone is created for the next major release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:783
msgid ""
"Bug reports in GitHub issues are automatically labelled ``bug`` and "
"``triage``. Spack developers assign one of the labels ``impact-low``, "
"``impact-medium`` or ``impact-high``. This will make the issue appear in the "
"`Triaged bugs <https://github.com/orgs/spack/projects/6>`_ project board. "
"Important issues should be assigned to the next milestone as well, so they "
"appear at the top of the project board."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:789
msgid ""
"Spack's milestones are not firm commitments so we move work between releases "
"frequently. If we need to make a release and some tasks are not yet done, we "
"will simply move them to the next major release milestone, rather than "
"delaying the release to complete them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:795
msgid "Backporting bug fixes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:797
msgid ""
"When a bug is fixed in the ``develop`` branch, it is often necessary to "
"backport the fix to one (or more) of the ``release/vX.Y`` branches. Only the "
"release manager is responsible for doing backports, but Spack maintainers "
"are responsible for labelling pull requests (and issues if no bug fix is "
"available yet) with ``vX.Y.Z`` labels. The label should correspond to the "
"next patch version that the bug fix should be backported to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:803
msgid ""
"Backports are done publicly by the release manager using a pull request "
"named ``Backports vX.Y.Z``. This pull request is opened from the ``backports/"
"vX.Y.Z`` branch, targets the ``releases/vX.Y`` branch and contains a "
"(growing) list of cherry-picked commits from the ``develop`` branch. "
"Typically there are one or two backport pull requests open at any given time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:812
msgid "Making major releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:814
msgid ""
"Assuming all required work from the milestone is completed, the steps to "
"make the major release are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:817
msgid ""
"`Create a new milestone <https://github.com/spack/spack/milestones>`_ for "
"the next major release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:820
msgid ""
"`Create a new label <https://github.com/spack/spack/labels>`_ for the next "
"patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:822
msgid "Move any optional tasks that are not done to the next milestone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:824
msgid "Create a branch for the release, based on ``develop``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:826
msgid "$ git checkout -b releases/v0.23 develop"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:830
msgid ""
"For a version ``vX.Y.Z``, the branch's name should be ``releases/vX.Y``. "
"That is, you should create a ``releases/vX.Y`` branch if you are preparing "
"the ``X.Y.0`` release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:834
msgid ""
"Remove the ``dev0`` development release segment from the version tuple in "
"``lib/spack/spack/__init__.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:837
msgid ""
"The version number itself should already be correct and should not be "
"modified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:840
msgid "Update ``CHANGELOG.md`` with major highlights in bullet form."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:842
msgid ""
"Use proper markdown formatting, like `this example from 0.15.0 <https://"
"github.com/spack/spack/commit/d4bf70d9882fcfe88507e9cb444331d7dd7ba71c>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:845
msgid "Push the release branch to GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:847
msgid "Make sure CI passes on the release branch, including:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:849 ../../../developer_guide.rst:930
msgid "Regular unit tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:850 ../../../developer_guide.rst:931
msgid "Build tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:851 ../../../developer_guide.rst:932
msgid "The E4S pipeline at `gitlab.spack.io <https://gitlab.spack.io>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:853
msgid ""
"If CI is not passing, submit pull requests to ``develop`` as normal and keep "
"rebasing the release branch on ``develop`` until CI passes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:856
msgid ""
"Make sure the entire documentation is up to date. If documentation is "
"outdated submit pull requests to ``develop`` as normal and keep rebasing the "
"release branch on ``develop``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:860
msgid "Bump the major version in the ``develop`` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:862
msgid ""
"Create a pull request targeting the ``develop`` branch, bumping the major "
"version in ``lib/spack/spack/__init__.py`` with a ``dev0`` release segment. "
"For instance when you have just released ``v0.23.0``, set the version to "
"``(0, 24, 0, 'dev0')`` on ``develop``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:867 ../../../developer_guide.rst:945
msgid "Follow the steps in :ref:`publishing-releases`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:869 ../../../developer_guide.rst:947
msgid "Follow the steps in :ref:`updating-latest-release`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:871 ../../../developer_guide.rst:949
msgid "Follow the steps in :ref:`announcing-releases`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:878
msgid "Making patch releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:880
msgid ""
"To make the patch release process both efficient and transparent, we use a "
"*backports pull request* which contains cherry-picked commits from the "
"``develop`` branch. The majority of the work is to cherry-pick the bug "
"fixes, which ideally should be done as soon as they land on ``develop``: "
"this ensures cherry-picking happens in order, and makes conflicts easier to "
"resolve since the changes are fresh in the mind of the developer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:886
msgid ""
"The backports pull request is always titled ``Backports vX.Y.Z`` and is "
"labelled ``backports``. It is opened from a branch named ``backports/vX.Y."
"Z`` and targets the ``releases/vX.Y`` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:889
msgid ""
"Whenever a pull request labelled ``vX.Y.Z`` is merged, cherry-pick the "
"associated squashed commit on ``develop`` to the ``backports/vX.Y.Z`` "
"branch. For pull requests that were rebased (or not squashed), cherry-pick "
"each associated commit individually. Never force push to the ``backports/vX."
"Y.Z`` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:896
msgid ""
"Sometimes you may **still** get merge conflicts even if you have cherry-"
"picked all the commits in order. This generally means there is some other "
"intervening pull request that the one you're trying to pick depends on. In "
"these cases, you'll need to make a judgment call regarding those pull "
"requests.  Consider the number of affected files and/or the resulting "
"differences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:903
msgid "If the changes are small, you might just cherry-pick it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:905
msgid ""
"If the changes are large, then you may decide that this fix is not worth "
"including in a patch release, in which case you should remove the label from "
"the pull request. Remember that large, manual backports are seldom the right "
"choice for a patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:910
msgid ""
"When all commits are cherry-picked in the ``backports/vX.Y.Z`` branch, make "
"the patch release as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:913
msgid ""
"`Create a new label <https://github.com/spack/spack/labels>`_ ``vX.Y.{Z+1}`` "
"for the next patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:916
msgid ""
"Replace the label ``vX.Y.Z`` with ``vX.Y.{Z+1}`` for all PRs and issues that "
"are not done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:918
msgid ""
"Manually push a single commit with commit message ``Set version to vX.Y.Z`` "
"to the ``backports/vX.Y.Z`` branch, that both bumps the Spack version number "
"and updates the changelog:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:921
msgid "Bump the version in ``lib/spack/spack/__init__.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:922
msgid "Update ``CHANGELOG.md`` with a list of the changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:924
msgid ""
"This is typically a summary of the commits you cherry-picked onto the "
"release branch. See `the changelog from 0.14.1 <https://github.com/spack/"
"spack/commit/ff0abb9838121522321df2a054d18e54b566b44a>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:928
msgid "Make sure CI passes on the **backports pull request**, including:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:934
msgid ""
"Merge the ``Backports vX.Y.Z`` PR with the **Rebase and merge** strategy. "
"This is needed to keep track in the release branch of all the commits that "
"were cherry-picked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:938
msgid "Make sure CI passes on the last commit of the **release branch**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:940
msgid ""
"In the rare case you need to include additional commits in the patch release "
"after the backports PR is merged, it is best to delete the last commit ``Set "
"version to vX.Y.Z`` from the release branch with a single force push, open a "
"new backports PR named ``Backports vX.Y.Z (2)``, and repeat the process. "
"Avoid repeated force pushes to the release branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:951
msgid ""
"Submit a PR to update the CHANGELOG in the `develop` branch with the "
"addition of this point release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:958
msgid "Publishing a release on GitHub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:960
msgid "Create the release in GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:962
msgid ""
"Go to `github.com/spack/spack/releases <https://github.com/spack/spack/"
"releases>`_ and click ``Draft a new release``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:966
msgid "Set ``Tag version`` to the name of the tag that will be created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:968
msgid ""
"The name should start with ``v`` and contain *all three* parts of the "
"version (e.g. ``v0.15.0`` or ``v0.15.1``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:971
msgid ""
"Set ``Target`` to the ``releases/vX.Y`` branch (e.g., ``releases/v0.15``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:973
msgid ""
"Set ``Release title`` to ``vX.Y.Z`` to match the tag (e.g., ``v0.15.1``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:975
msgid ""
"Paste the latest release markdown from your ``CHANGELOG.md`` file as the "
"text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:977
msgid ""
"Save the draft so you can keep coming back to it as you prepare the release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:979
msgid "When you are ready to finalize the release, click ``Publish release``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:981
msgid ""
"Immediately after publishing, go back to `github.com/spack/spack/releases "
"<https://github.com/spack/spack/releases>`_ and download the auto-generated "
"``.tar.gz`` file for the release. It's the ``Source code (tar.gz)`` link."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:987
msgid ""
"Click ``Edit`` on the release you just made and attach the downloaded "
"release tarball as a binary. This does two things:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:990
msgid "Makes sure that the hash of our releases does not change over time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:992
msgid ""
"GitHub sometimes annoyingly changes the way they generate tarballs that can "
"result in the hashes changing if you rely on the auto-generated tarball "
"links."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:996
msgid "Gets download counts on releases visible through the GitHub API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:998
msgid ""
"GitHub tracks downloads of artifacts, but *not* the source links. See the "
"`releases page <https://api.github.com/repos/spack/spack/releases>`_ and "
"search for ``download_count`` to see this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1003
msgid ""
"Go to `readthedocs.org <https://readthedocs.org/projects/spack>`_ and "
"activate the release tag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1006
msgid ""
"This builds the documentation and makes the released version selectable in "
"the versions menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1014
msgid "Updating `releases/latest`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1016
msgid ""
"If the new release is the **highest** Spack release yet, you should also tag "
"it as ``releases/latest``. For example, suppose the highest release is "
"currently ``0.22.3``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1020
msgid ""
"If you are releasing ``0.22.4`` or ``0.23.0``, then you should tag it with "
"``releases/latest``, as these are higher than ``0.22.3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1023
msgid ""
"If you are making a new release of an **older** major version of Spack, e.g. "
"``0.21.4``, then you should not tag it as ``releases/latest`` (as there are "
"newer major versions)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1027
msgid ""
"To do so, first fetch the latest tag created on GitHub, since you may not "
"have it locally:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1029
msgid "$ git fetch --force git@github.com:spack/spack vX.Y.Z"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1033
msgid ""
"Then tag ``vX.Y.Z`` as ``releases/latest`` and push the individual tag to "
"GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1035
msgid ""
"$ git tag --force releases/latest vX.Y.Z\n"
"$ git push --force git@github.com:spack/spack releases/latest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1040
msgid ""
"The ``--force`` argument to ``git tag`` makes ``git`` overwrite the existing "
"``releases/latest`` tag with the new one. Do **not** use the ``--tags`` flag "
"when pushing, since this will push *all* local tags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1049
msgid "Announcing a release"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1051
msgid ""
"We announce releases in all of the major Spack communication channels. "
"Publishing the release takes care of GitHub. The remaining channels are X, "
"Slack, and the mailing list. Here are the steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1055
msgid "Announce the release on X."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1057
msgid ""
"Compose the tweet on the ``@spackpm`` account per the ``spack-twitter`` "
"slack channel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1060 ../../../developer_guide.rst:1082
msgid "Be sure to include a link to the release's page on GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1062
msgid ""
"You can base the tweet on `this example <https://twitter.com/spackpm/"
"status/1231761858182307840>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1065
msgid "Announce the release on Slack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1067
msgid ""
"Compose a message in the ``#general`` Slack channel (`spackpm.slack.com "
"<https://spackpm.slack.com>`_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1070
msgid ""
"Preface the message with ``@channel`` to notify even those people not "
"currently logged in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1073
msgid "Be sure to include a link to the tweet above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1075
msgid ""
"The tweet will be shown inline so that you do not have to retype your "
"release announcement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1078
msgid "Announce the release on the Spack mailing list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1080
msgid "Compose an email to the Spack mailing list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1084
msgid "It is also helpful to include some information directly in the email."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1087
msgid ""
"You can base your announcement on this `example email <https://groups.google."
"com/forum/#!topic/spack/WT4CT9i_X4s>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:1090
msgid ""
"Once you've completed the above steps, congratulations, you're done! You've "
"finished making the release!"
msgstr ""
